<div id="review_1196967710" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1196967710" />
    <a title="Karis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38975931-karis"><img alt="Karis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546018277p2/38975931.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1196967710?book_show_action=true">Feb 10, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karis" href="/user/show/38975931-karis">Karis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780399244544" href="/book/show/824729.The_Ruins_of_Gorlan">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38975931-karis?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38975931-karis?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38975931-karis?shelf=friendships">friendships</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38975931-karis?shelf=mentors">mentors</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1196967710" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2519774821808035858">John Flanagan is a well known author of several different genres, but probably some of his best known books are the Ranger’s Apprentice series. They have definitely caused millions of readers to sigh wistfully and wish themselves Rangers. I know I have, and I’m not sure why it has taken me so long to review The Ruins of Gorlan, the first book in the RA series. <br/><br/> Will is worried. Tomorrow is Choosing Day, the day when the wards at Redmont Castle were chosen by the Craftmasters as apprentices. He’s</span>
  <span id="freeText2519774821808035858" style="display:none">John Flanagan is a well known author of several different genres, but probably some of his best known books are the Ranger’s Apprentice series. They have definitely caused millions of readers to sigh wistfully and wish themselves Rangers. I know I have, and I’m not sure why it has taken me so long to review The Ruins of Gorlan, the first book in the RA series. <br /><br /> Will is worried. Tomorrow is Choosing Day, the day when the wards at Redmont Castle were chosen by the Craftmasters as apprentices. He’s thoughts go to his four fellow ward mates. George is quiet but smart with neat handwriting and destined for the Scribeschool. Jenny is a sweet bubbly girl with a love for cooking- destined for the kitchen under Master Chubb. Alyss, always a diplomat, destined to train under Lady Pauline in the Diplomat Services. Horace with his large form destined for Battleschool. That left Will, not gifted with any of the talents of his friends or with the height needed for Battleschool.<br /><br /> His fears are justified the next day when his friends are apprenticed but he isn’t accepted by the any of the Craftmasters. However, the ever silent and grim Ranger Halt, steps out of the shadows and address the Baron. He hands a piece of paper to Baron Arald saying that there was something the Baron needed to know about Will.<br /><br /> Will spends the rest of the day in misery, despite the jovial and festive attitude of his friends. The only prospect he can see is spending his life as a field hand in the village. Will’s curiosity is kindled about what Halt could possibility know about him and he decides to climb one of Redmount’s towers to get to Baron’s personal offices to the piece of paper. “The sheet of paper, bright white with the reflected moonlight, was within reach…. His fingers touched it. And a hand shot out of nowhere and seized him by the wrist! Will shouted aloud in fright. His heart leaped into his mouth and he found himself looking up into the cold eyes of Halt the Ranger.” (page 37)<br /><br /> Halt brings Will before the Baron and when Will is given the paper to read this is what it says: <i>The boy Will has the potential to be trained as a Ranger. I will accept him as my apprentice. </i> Little does Will know that those words will change his life forever and become the start of an epic adventure. <br /><br /> The book is mainly from Will’s POV but some of the later chapters are from Horace’s perspective. I was a little inpatient to get back to Will. However, I realized that those chapters were important as well as written well. If you haven’t read the Ranger’s Apprentice series yet I really recommend you start soon. The series is full of clean humor and has some really descriptive details that are quite fascinating, not to mention the gripping plot line.<br /><br /> P.S. If you are interested in joining a Goodreads fan group for the RA series. Join here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/group/show/189838">https://www.goodreads.com/group/show/...</a> I would really appreciate it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2519774821808035858" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


